edal]]\n}}\n'''Ronald Dion \"Ron\" DeSantis''' (born September 14, 1978) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] for {{ushr|FL|6}} since 2013. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he ran in [[United States Senate election in Florida, 2016|Florida's 2016 U.S. Senate election]]; however, DeSantis withdrew from the race following incumbent Senator [[Marco Rubio]]'s announcement that he would seek reelection to the Senate, reversing his initial pledge not to run, on June 22, 2016.<ref name=\"DeSantisRuns\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2016/06/22/marco-rubio-will-seek-senate-re-election-reversing-pledge-not-to-run/|title=Marco Rubio will seek Senate reelection, reversing pledge not to run|publisher=The Washington Post|last1=DeBonis|first1=Mike|last2=O'Keefe|first2=Ed|last3=Sullivan|first3=Sean|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"DeSantisRunsTwo\">{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/214270-whats-ron-desantis-next-move-stay-tuned|title=Reports: Ron DeSantis to run for re-election in CD 6|publisher=Florida Politics|last=Gancarski|first=A.G.|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref> After Rubio's decision to re-enter the U.S. Senate race, DeSantis opted to run for re-election to his U.S. House seat in [[Florida's 6th congressional district]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kopan|first1=Tal|title=Another GOP challenger clears way for Marco Rubio|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/24/politics/marco-rubio-senate-todd-wilcox/|accessdate=29 June 2016|publisher=CNN|date=June 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRon DeSantis was born in 1978 in [[Jacksonville, Florida]]. In 1991 he was a member of the [[Little League]] team from Dunedin National that made it to the [[Little League World Series]] in [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzales|first1=Nathan|title=Fall Elections Shape Future Rosters|url=http://www.rollcall.com/features/Baseball-Program_2012/baseball/Fall-Elections-Shape-Future-Rosters-215692-1.html|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Roll Call|date=June 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Vaccaro|first1=Ron|title=Baseball\u2019s DeSantis shines on Yale Field of dreams|url=http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2001/03/30/baseballs-desantis-shines-on-yale-field-of-dreams/|accessdate=26 February 2016|publisher=Yale News|date=March 30, 2001}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from [[Dunedin High School]] in [[Dunedin, Florida|Dunedin]] in 1997. He pursued his higher education at [[Yale University]], where he was captain of the [[Yale baseball team|varsity baseball team]] in his senior year. He was also a member of the [[Phi]] chapter of [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]] at Yale University, the same fraternity as five former U.S. Presidents including [[George W. Bush]]. He graduated [[magna cum laude]] with a B.A. in History in 2001. He earned a J.D. from [[Harvard Law School]] cum laude in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/137630/ron-desantis|title=Ron DeSantis' Biography - The Voter's Self Defense System|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\nDeSantis was sworn into the Judge Advocate General Corps of the [[U.S. Navy]] at the U.S. Naval Reserve Center in [[Dallas, Texas]], in 2004 while still a student at Harvard Law School, completing [[Naval Justice School|U.S. Naval Justice School]] in 2005. Later that year, he received orders from Trial Service Office Command South East at the [[Naval Station Mayport]], Florida, as a [[military justice|military prosecutor]]. In 2006, he was promoted to Lieutenant (O-3). He worked for the [[Joint Task Force Guantanamo|Joint Task Force-Guantanamo Commander]] (JTF-GTMO), working directly with detainees at the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay Joint Detention Facility]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perry|first1=Mitch|title=Group sponsoring Ron DeSantis appearance in Tampa denounced for associations with the Koch Brothers|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/211058-group-sponsoring-ron-desantis-appearance-tampa-denounced-associations-koch-brothers|accessdate=27 May 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=May 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, DeSantis reported to the [[Naval Special Warfare Command|Naval Special Warfare Command Group]] in [[Coronado, California]], where he was assigned to [[SEAL Team One]] and deployed to [[Iraq War of 2003|Iraq]]<ref name=farrington>{{cite news|last1=Farrington|first1=Brenda|title=Republican Congressman DeSantis to run for Rubio Senate seat|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-ap-senate-florida-desantis-20150505-story.html|accessdate=27 May 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Sun Sentinel|date=May 5, 2015}}</ref> with the [[Iraq troop surge|troop surge]] as the Legal Advisor to the SEAL Commander, [[Special Operations Task Force|Special Operations Task Force-West]] in [[Fallujah]].\n\nHe returned to [[CONUS]] in April 2008, at which time he was reassigned to the Naval Region Legal Service. He was appointed by the [[U.S. Department of Justice]] to serve as a [[federal prosecutor]]<ref name=farrington/> at the [[U.S. Attorney for the Middle District of Florida|U.S. Attorney\u2019s Office in the Middle District of Florida]].\n\nDeSantis was assigned as a Trial Defense Counsel until his honorable discharge from active duty in February 2010. He concurrently accepted a Reserve commission as a Lieutenant, Judge Advocate General Corps, in the [[US Navy Reserve]].<ref name=wsj/> He was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal]] and the [[Iraq Campaign Medal]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Congressman Ron DeSantis|url=http://combatveteransforcongress.org/cand/2790|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Combat Veterans for America}}</ref>\n\n==Writing and teaching==\nHe authored a book entitled ''Dreams From Our Founding Fathers: First Principles in the Age of Obama,'' which was published in 2011.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|title=Ron DeSantis (R)|url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/ron-desantis--FL-H|accessdate=27 May 2016|work=Election 2012|publisher=Wall Street Journal}}</ref> He has taught [[Uniform Code of Military Justice|U.S. Military Law]] at [[Florida Coastal School of Law]] in Jacksonville.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gizzi|first1=John|title=DeSantis aims for change|url=http://humanevents.com/2013/01/25/desantis-aims-for-change/|accessdate=27 May 2016|publisher=Human Events|date=January 25, 2013}}</ref> His writing has appeared in ''[[National Review]]'', ''[[The Washington Times]]'', ''[[The American Spectator]]'', ''[[Human Events]]'', and ''[[American Thinker]]''.<ref name=wsj/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2012 election===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2012#District 6}}\nRedistricting left [[Florida's 6th congressional district]] without an incumbent, and DeSantis chose to run for the open seat. He won the six-candidate Republican primary with 39% of the vote, with the runner-up, State Representative [[Fred Costello]], obtaining 23%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=756561|title=FL District 06 - R Primary Race|date=August 14, 2012|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref> In the November general election, DeSantis defeated Democrat [[Heather Beaven]] by 57%-43%, with majorities in all four counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=736113|title=FL District 06 Race|date=November 6, 2012|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nPrior to the [[114th United States Congress]], DeSantis was named the Chairman of the [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on National Security|Subcommittee on National Security]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Despite Opposing 'CRomnibus,' Sophomore Ron DeSantis Ascends Congressional Ladder|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/despite-opposing-cromnibus-sophomore-ron-desantis-ascends-congressional-ladder|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=December 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia|Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere|Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice|Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice]]\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet|Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Federal Workforce, U.S. Postal Service and the Census|Subcommittee on Federal Workforce, U.S. Postal Service and the Census]]\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs|Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs]]\n\n===Legislation===\nOn January 29, 2014, DeSantis introduced into the House the [[Faithful Execution of the Law Act of 2014 (H.R. 3973; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[United States Department of Justice]] to report to the [[United States Congress]] whenever any [[List of United States federal agencies|federal agency]] refrains from enforcing laws or regulations for any reason.<ref name=3973cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3973 \u2013 CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45177|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=3972sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3972 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3973|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref> In the report, the government would have to explain why it had decided not to enforce that law.<ref name=HtargetsObamalawEnf>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House targets Obama's law enforcement|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/government-oversight/200167-house-to-attack-obamas-non-enforcement-next-week|accessdate=March 12, 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=March 7, 2014}}</ref> DeSantis spoke in favor of the bill, arguing that \"President Obama has not only failed to uphold several of our nation's laws, he has vowed to continue to do so in order to enact his unpopular agenda... The American people deserve to know exactly which laws the Obama administration is refusing to enforce and why.\"<ref name=\"HtargetsObamalawEnf\"/>\n\nIn 2013, DeSantis signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any global warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americansforprosperity.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/DeSantis_Ron.pdf|title=Americans for Prosperity Applauds U.S. Representative Ron DeSantis|accessdate=October 8, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015194819/http://americansforprosperity.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/DeSantis_Ron.pdf|archivedate=October 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, DeSantis spoke at a [[Ripon Society]] forum and addressed the [[IRS targeting controversy]] and tax reform. DeSantis echoed his colleagues on understanding the main part of government, saying: \"Part of having a constitutional government is that you have an accountable government.\" He went on to say that he \"think(s) we make a huge mistake if we try to generate political outcomes, thinking that it will help us politically or that we're trying to bring somebody down. I think it\u2019s necessary if we are just trying to find the truth and hold individuals accountable. I think we need to see more of that in this government.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riponsociety.org/news_5-21-13.htm|title=This is something that sends chills down regular Americans\u2019 spines|date=May 21, 2013|publisher=The Ripon Society|accessdate=June 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==2016 U.S. Senate candidacy==\n{{main article|United States Senate election in Florida, 2016}}\nOn May 6, 2015, DeSantis announced that he was running for the [[United States Senate]] seat held by [[Marco Rubio]], who initially did not file to run for re-election due to [[Marco Rubio presidential campaign, 2016|his bid]] for the [[President of the United States|U.S. presidency]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Letitia|title=Florida Congressman Ron DeSantis running for U.S. Senate|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/05/06/us-usa-election-florida-senate-idUSKBN0NR1S420150506|accessdate=7 May 2015|publisher=Reuters|date=May 6, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis was endorsed by the fiscally conservative [[Club for Growth]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Video: Club for Growth backs DeSantis|url=http://thehill.com/video/in-the-news/241205-video-club-for-growth-backs-desantis|accessdate=3 June 2015|publisher=The Hill|date=May 6, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis withdrew from the race following incumbent Senator [[Marco Rubio]]'s announcement that he would seek reelection to the Senate, reversing his initial pledge not to run, on June 22, 2016.<ref name=\"DeSantisRuns\"/><ref name=\"DeSantisRunsTwo\"/> After dropping his U.S. Senate bid, DeSantis filed to run for re-election to his U.S. House seat.\n\n==Policy positions==\n\n===National security===\nDeSantis believes that \"Providing security against foreign danger is the preeminent responsibility of the federal government.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=National Defense|url=https://www.desantis2016.com/issues/national-defense|publisher=Ron DeSantis|accessdate=February 26, 2016}}</ref> DeSantis's 2016 U.S. Senate bid was endorsed by former [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[John R. Bolton]], who cited DeSantis's support of a strong national defense, opposition to the Iran nuclear framework, defense of Israel, and criticism of the Obama administration's Cuba policy as reasons for the endorsement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Torres|first1=Frank|title=Former Ambassador John Bolton Endorses DeSantis|url=http://orlando-politics.com/2015/05/07/former-ambassador-john-bolton-endorses-desantis|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=The Orlando Political Observer|date=May 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Iran====\nDeSantis opposed the [[Iran nuclear deal framework]], calling it \"a bad deal that will significantly degrade our national security.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cotton|first1=Tom|last2=DeSantis|first2=Ron|title=Congress Must Reject the Iran Deal|url=http://time.com/3978510/congress-must-reject-the-iran-deal/|accessdate=26 February 2016|publisher=Time|date=July 30, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis said \"the Iran deal gives Ayatollah Khamenei exactly what he wants: billions of dollars in sanctions relief, validation of the Iranian nuclear program, and the ability to stymie inspections.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=DeSantis Condemns Deal as a Gift to Iran's Ayatollah|url=https://desantis.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/desantis-condemns-deal-as-a-gift-to-irans-ayatollah|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Congressman Ron DeSantis|date=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring a line of questioning, DeSantis told Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] that the executive branch had a legal obligation to provide Congress with the details behind any side deals made between world leaders and Iran.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Torres|first1=Frank|title=DeSantis and Kerry get contentious over Iran Deal|url=http://orlando-politics.com/2015/07/29/desantis-and-kerry-get-contentious-over-iran-deal/|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Orlando Political Observer|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis has criticized President Barack Obama for what he said was better treatment of Cuba's [[Raul Castro]] and Iran's Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] than of Israel's [[Benjamin Netanyahu]].<ref name=save>{{cite news|last1=Man|first1=Anthony|title='We need to save the country,' conservative U.S. Senate candidate tells Broward activists|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-ron-desantis-conservative-candidate-20150824-story.html|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sun Sentinel|date=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Cuba====\nIn 2015, DeSantis introduced the Guantanamo Bay Recidivism Prevention Act, which would cut off foreign aid to countries that receive detainees if they show back up on the terrorism recidivism list.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Ron DeSantis: Releasing Guantanamo Detainees is a Security Threat|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/blog/ron-desanits-releasing-guantanamo-detainees-security-threat|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=January 14, 2016}}</ref> DeSantis opposed President Obama's plan to shut down the terrorist holding facility at the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay]] military base, saying \"Bringing hardened terrorists to the U.S. homeland harms our national security.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Obama's GITMO Proposal Draws Fire From GOP Candidates Vying to Replace Marco Rubio|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/obamas-gitmo-propsoal-draws-fire-gop-candidates-vying-replace-marco-rubio|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=February 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRegarding the formal restart of diplomatic relations between the U.S. and Cuba, DeSantis said \"Raising the Cuban flag in the United States is a slap in the face to those who have experienced the brutality of the Castro regime.\"<ref name=reaction>{{cite news|last1=Leary|first1=Alex|title=Florida reaction to Cuba news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/florida-reaction-to-cuba-news/2237995|accessdate=26 February 2016|publisher=Tampa Bay Times|date=July 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Israel====\nIn 2013, DeSantis introduced the Palestinian Accountability Act, which would halt U.S. aid to the [[Palestinian National Authority|Palestinian Authority]] until it formally recognizes [[Israel]]\u2019s right to exist as a Jewish state and cuts off all ties with the terror group [[Hamas]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kredo|first1=Adam|title=House Bill Would Cut Aid to Palestinian Authority|url=http://freebeacon.com/national-security/house-bill-would-cut-aid-to-palestinian-authority|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Washington Free Beacon|date=March 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, DeSantis co-introduced the Non-Discrimination of Israel in Labeling Act, which will defend the right of Israeli producers to label products manufactured in the West Bank as \u201cIsrael,\u201d \u201cMade in Israel,\u201d or \u201cProduct of Israel.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ganckarski|first1=A.G.|title=Ron DeSantis co-introduces non-discrimination of Israel in labeling act|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/201890-ron-desantis-co-introduces-non-discrimination-of-israel-in-labeling-act|accessdate=26 February 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=February 16, 2016}}</ref> DeSantis believes that the U.S. Embassy should be moved from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Klein Greenwald|first1=Toby|title=Two GOP Congress members visit Israel, pledge support|url=http://www.sdjewishworld.com/2014/05/16/two-gop-congressmen-visit-israel-pledge-support|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=San Diego Jewish World|date=May 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Islamic terrorism====\nAfter the [[November 2015 Paris attacks]], DeSantis \"called for urgent recognition that Islamic extremism is to blame for the Paris attacks and should be seen as an enemy for America.\" DeSantis has said \"The enemy is an ideology rooted in militant Islam\" and has said that [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]] must be stopped and its members kept away from America.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Powers|first1=Scott|title=GOP Senate candidates call for fight against Islamic militants after Paris attacks|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-sunshine-summit-senate-candidates-20151114-story.html|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Orlando Sentinel|date=November 14, 2015}}</ref> In December 2015, DeSantis introduced the Terrorist Refugee Infiltration Prevention Act, which would prevent refugees from countries with terrorist-controlled areas from entering into the United States.\n\nThe bill includes an exception for refugees who are a member of a group that is a victim of genocide.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fields|first1=Michelle|title=Rep. Ron DeSantis Introduces Bill to Stop Refugees from Syria|url=http://www.breitbart.com/big-government/2015/12/01/rep-ron-desantis-introduces-bill-stop-refugees-syria/|accessdate=26 February 2016|publisher=Breitbart|date=December 1, 2015}}</ref> Regarding U.S. policy toward refugees, DeSantis said \"the prudent policy is to err on the side of protecting the American people.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Rep. Ron DeSantis on refugee debate: 'Err on side of protecting the American people'|url=http://www.foxnews.com/transcript/2015/11/27/rep-ron-desantis-on-refugee-debate-err-on-side-protecting-american-people/|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Fox News|date=November 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Veterans affairs===\nDeSantis has sharply criticized the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] for the [[Veterans Health Administration scandal of 2014]], in which veteran deaths were linked to fatal wait times. He co-sponsored the VA Accountability Act, which aims to increase accountability by providing for the removal or demotion of employees of the Department of Veterans Affairs based on performance or misconduct.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winslow|first1=Hailey|title=Congressman Ron DeSantis pushes legislation to hold Veterans Affairs accountable|url=http://www.news4jax.com/news/florida/st-johns-county/congressman-ron-desantis-pushes-legislation-to-hold-veterans-affairs-accountable|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=News 4 Jax|date=May 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Clifford|title=Rep. Ron DeSantis pushes for VA reform in St. Augustine|url=http://jacksonville.com/news/politics/2014-05-05/story/rep-ron-desantis-pushes-va-reform-st-augustine|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Florida Times Union|date=May 5, 2014}}</ref> He is a member of the Post-9/11 Veterans Caucus.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Porter|first1=Thomas|title=IAVA Team Continues to Seek Path Forward for 9/11 First Responders|url=http://iava.org/blogs/iava-team-continues-to-seek-path-forward-for-911-first-responders-press-conference-tomorrow|publisher=Iraq & Afghanistan Veterans of America|accessdate=February 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\nDeSantis is opposed to the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], which he believes should be replaced with policies designed to strengthen Medicare, facilitate consumer choice, and reduce costs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rep. DeSantis Statement on ObamaCare Repeal|url=https://desantis.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-desantis-statement-on-obamacare-repeal|publisher=Ron DeSantis|accessdate=February 27, 2016}}</ref> His own health care reform proposals include creating a refundable universal tax credit for health insurance purchases, using high risk pools to provide coverage options for \npeople with preexisting conditions, allowing individuals to choose health insurance plans without government involvement, prohibiting the [[Internal Revenue Service]] from having involvement in health care decisions, barring the use of taxpayer funds to bail out insurance companies, and \nblock granting [[Medicaid]] to the states.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moorhead|first1=Molly|title=Florida Rep. Ron DeSantis says \u2018Obamacare\u2019 tax is cheaper than insurance|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2013/jan/24/ron-desantis/desantis-says-obamacare-tax-cheaper-insurance/|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=PolitiFact|date=January 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis co-sponsored a bill to end congressional exemptions from Obamacare, treating members of Congress and their staffers the same as every other American under the law.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Ron DeSantis Leads the Charge Against Congressional Obamacare Exemptions|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/ron-desantis-leads-charge-against-congressional-obamacare-exemptions|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=April 21, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis introduced a proposed 28th Amendment to the Constitution that would prohibit members of Congress from exempting themselves from laws that apply to the rest of the country.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reps. DeSantis and Salmon Introduce Constitutional Amendment to Hold Washington Accountable|url=https://desantis.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/reps-desantis-and-salmon-introduce-constitutional-amendment-to-hold|accessdate=February 29, 2016|publisher=Congressman Ron DeSantis|date=August 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Romano|first1=Aja|title=Internet users demand politicians abide by fictional 28th Amendment|url=http://www.dailydot.com/politics/fake-28th-amendment-government-shutdown-protest|accessdate=February 29, 2016|publisher=Daily Dot|date=October 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nDeSantis believes the U.S. should enforce existing immigration laws and secure the border. He supports a  visa tracking system to prevent individuals from illegally overstaying visas. He opposes executive amnesty and the release of convicted criminals who are in the U.S. illegally.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Ron DeSantis Turns Up the Heat on Obama for Failing to Enforce Immigration Laws|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/ron-desantis-turns-heat-obama-failing-enforce-immigration-laws|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=February 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Scanlon|first1=Kate|title=Before Skeptical Lawmakers, Officials Defend 'Legality' of Obama's Immigration Actions|url=http://dailysignal.com/2015/06/17/before-skeptical-lawmakers-officials-defend-legality-of-obamas-immigration-actions|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=The Daily Signal|date=June 17, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis opposes sanctuary cities.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u2190 Shrink player Sanctuary cities under fire|url=http://video.foxbusiness.com/v/4358373421001/sanctuary-cities-under-fire-/?#sp=show-clips|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Fox News|date=July 16, 2015}}</ref> He is a co-sponsor of the Establishing Mandatory Minimums for Illegal Reentry Act of 2015, also known as Kate's Law, which would amend the Immigration and Nationality Act to increase penalties applicable to aliens who unlawfully reenter the United States after being removed.<ref>{{cite web|title=US - HR3011 Kate's Law|url=https://trackbill.com/bill/us-hr3011-kates-law/1198394/?utm_expid=81892712-9.nw2hkUbvSTujoX9vrv6AMQ.0&utm_referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com|publisher=TrackBill|accessdate=February 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Size and scope of government===\nDeSantis opted not to receive his [[congressional pension]], and he filed a measure that would eliminate pensions for members of Congress.<ref name=roll/> After introducing the End Pensions in Congress Act, DeSantis said \"The Founding Fathers envisioned elected officials as part of a servant class, yet Washington has evolved into a ruling class culture.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harper|first1=Jennifer|title=No more \u2018ruling class culture\u2019: New legislation would jettison pensions for Congress|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/feb/2/no-more-ruling-class-culture-new-legislaiton-would/|accessdate=28 February 2016|publisher=Washington Times|date=February 2, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis believes term limits should exist for members of Congress.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Farrington|first1=Brendan|title=Republican Congressman DeSantis to run for Rubio Senate seat|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-ap-senate-florida-desantis-20150505-story.html|accessdate=February 28, 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Sun Sentinel|date=May 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe sponsored the [[Faithful Execution of the Law Act of 2014]], which would direct the United States Department of Justice to report to the United States Congress whenever any federal agency refrains from enforcing laws or regulations for any reason. Speaking about the bill, DeSantis said \"You can not have rule of law when people don\u2019t know what the law is.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lucas|first1=Fred|title=GOP Congressman: Obama Veto Threats Inconsistent With His Oath to Execute the Law|url=http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2014/03/12/gop-congressman-obama-veto-threats-inconsistent-with-his-oath-to-execute-the-law|accessdate=February 29, 2016|publisher=The Blaze|date=March 12, 2014}}</ref> The bill passed the U.S. House in March 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Ron DeSantis' Faithful Execution of the Law Act Passes House|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/blog/ron-desantis-faithful-execution-law-act-passes-house|accessdate=February 29, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=March 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Economic issues===\nDeSantis has said that the debate in Washington, D.C. over how to reduce the deficit should shift emphasis from tax increases to curtailing spending and triggering economic growth.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jordan|first1=Douglas|title=DeSantis emphasizes importance of economic growth|url=http://staugustine.com/news/local-news/2012-12-15/desantis-economic-growth-essential#.VtN1cPHvOad|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=St. Augustine Record|date=December 16, 2012}}</ref> DeSantis supports a \u201cno budget no pay\u201d policy for Congress to encourage the passage of a budget.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wexler|first1=Gene|title=New St. Johns Rep. opens up on financial and governmental reforms|url=http://www.wokv.com/news/news/local/new-st-johns-rep-opens-financial-and-governmental-/nTmcb/|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=WOKV|date=January 3, 2013}}</ref> He believes the [[Federal Reserve System]] should be audited.<ref name=roll/>\n\nIn the wake of the [[IRS targeting controversy]], DeSantis called for the resignation of Internal Revenue Service Commissioner [[John Koskinen]] for having \"failed the American people by frustrating Congress\u2019s attempts to ascertain the truth.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=DeSantis|first1=Ron|last2=Jordan|first2=Jim|title=The Stonewall at the Top of the IRS|url=http://www.wsj.com/articles/the-stonewall-at-the-top-of-the-irs-1438039060|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=July 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Perry|first1=Mitch|title=Ron DeSantis wants Obama to remove IRS commissioner \u2014 or else|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/187207-ron-desantis-wants-obama-to-remove-irs-commissioner-or-else|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=July 28, 2015}}</ref> He co-sponsored a bill to impeach Koskinen for violating the public's trust.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://oversight.house.gov/release/resolution-introduced-impeach-irs-commissioner|title=Resolution Introduced to Impeach IRS Commissioner|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=House Oversight Committee|date=October 27, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, DeSantis was named \"Taxpayer Superhero\" by [[Citizens Against Government Waste]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gancarski|first1=July 31, 2015|title=Email insights: Ron DeSantis, \"Taxpayer Superhero\"|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/187434-email-insights-ron-desantis-taxpayer-superhero|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=July 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis supported the REINS Act, which would require that regulations that have a significant economic impact be subject to a vote of Congress prior to taking effect.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siefring|first1=Neil|title=The REINS Act will keep regulations and their costs in check|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/economy-budget/250178-the-reins-act-will-keep-regulations-and-their-costs-in|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=The Hill|date=August 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis introduced the Let Seniors Work Act, which would repeal the Retirement Earnings Test and stop the 12.4% payroll tax for working seniors, and he co-sponsored a measure to eliminate taxes on [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] benefits.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Marco Rubio, Ron DeSantis Restore 'Let Seniors Work Act'|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/marco-rubio-ron-desantis-restore-let-seniors-work-act|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=March 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis sponsored the Transportation Empowerment Act, which would  transfer much of the responsibility for transportation projects to the individual states. The bill would reduce the gas tax.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Laing|first1=Keith|title=Bill filed to sharply reduce the gas tax|url=http://thehill.com/policy/transportation/244597-bill-filed-to-eliminate-the-gas-tax|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=The Hill|date=June 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Mike|last2=DeSantis|first2=Ron|title=Economy Commentary Let America Fix the Highways Washington Broke|url=http://dailysignal.com/2015/06/10/let-america-fix-the-highways-washington-broke|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=The Daily Signal|date=June 10, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis has opposed taxes on the internet, including legislation that would require online retailers to pay state sales tax.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dixon|first1=Matt|title=Retail group assails DeSantis over Internet sales tax|url=http://staugustine.com/news/local-news/2013-06-27#.VtONM_HvOac|accessdate=February 29, 2016|publisher=St. Augustine Record|date=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Social issues===\nDeSantis is [[United States pro-life movement|pro-life]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gehkre|first1=Joel|title=Planned Parenthood Head: An Abortion Survivor is a 'Baby' Entitled to Medical Care|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/424801/planned-parenthood-chief-abortion-survivor-baby-entitled-medical-care-joel-gehrke|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=National Review|date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> He opposes taxpayer funding of [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gancarski|first1=A.G.|title=Ron DeSantis denounces Planned Parenthood\u2019s alleged \"loathsome practice\"|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/186587-ron-desantis-denounces-planned-parenthoods-loathsome-practice|accessdate=27 February 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=July 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Berry|first1=Susan|title=House Freedom Caucus: 'We Oppose Any Spending Measure' That Funds Planned Parenthood|url=http://www.breitbart.com/big-government/2015/09/11/house-freedom-caucus-we-oppose-any-spending-measure-that-funds-planned-parenthood/|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Breitbart|date=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nCiting the importance of [[Freedom of religion|religious freedom]], DeSantis has said the government should protect companies whose owners want to exclude birth control from their employees' health insurance coverage, and refrain from applying anti-discrimination laws to individuals or entities who discriminate against gay people.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Torres|first1=Frank|title=Ron DeSantis endorsed by Common Core opponent FRC Action PAC|url=http://orlando-politics.com/2015/11/23/ron-desantis-endorsed-by-common-core-opponent-frc-action-pac/|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=The Orlando Political Observer|date=November 23, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis agreed with the U.S. Supreme Court's decision in ''[[Burwell v. Hobby Lobby Stores, Inc.]]'', saying \"This case does not concern the availability or legality of contraceptives, and individuals can obtain and use these as they see fit. The question is simply whether the government can force the owners of Hobby Lobby to pay for abortifacients in violation of their faith.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Florida Congressmen Divide Over Hobby Lobby Case|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/florida-congressmen-divide-over-hobby-lobby-case|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=March 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Second Amendment===\nDeSantis opposes [[gun control]]. He received an A+ rating from the [[National Rifle Association]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Keller|first1=Michael|title=This is Your Representative on Guns|url=http://thedailybeast.thisisyourreponguns.com/#Pane=overview&Chamber=House|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=The Daily Beast|date=February 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nDeSantis opposes federal education programs such as [[No Child Left Behind Act]] and [[Race to the Top]], saying that education policy should be made at the local level.<ref name=roll>{{cite news|title=Ron DeSantis, R-Fla. (6th District)|url=http://www.rollcall.com/new-members/ron-desantis-house-r-fla-6.html|accessdate=28 February 2016|publisher=Roll Call}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis introduced the Higher Education Reform and Opportunity Act, which would allow states to create their own accreditation systems in an effort to open up an alternative market for education that gives students access to federal loan money to put towards non-traditional educational opportunities, such as online learning courses, vocational schools, and apprenticeships in skilled trades.<ref>{{cite news|last1=DeSantis|first1=Ron|last2=Lee|first2=Mike|title=Break Up the Higher-Ed Cartel|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/414848/break-higher-ed-cartel-ron-desantis-mike-lee|accessdate=February 29, 2016|publisher=National Review|date=March 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2010, DeSantis married Casey Black, a local [[Emmy Award|Emmy]]-winning television host. They previously lived in [[Ponte Vedra Beach, Florida]].<ref name=save/> However, DeSantis and his wife moved to [[Palm Coast, Florida]] in July, 2016 after redistricting moved their home in Ponte Vedra Beach into the 4th congressional district.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Harper |url=http://www.news-journalonline.com/news/20160729/congressman-ron-desantis-moves-to-flagler-county |title=Congressman Ron DeSantis moves to Flagler County - News - Daytona Beach News-Journal Online - Daytona Beach, FL |website=News-journalonline.com |date=2016-09-30 |accessdate=2016-10-18}}</ref><ref>[https://floridaresidentdb.com/person/107083209/ronald_dion_desantis] {{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://desantis.house.gov/ Congressman Ron DeSantis] official U.S. House website\n* [https://www.desantis2016.com/ Campaign website]\n* {{C-SPAN|rondesantis}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = D000621 | ballot = Ron_DeSantis | nndb = | votesmart = 137630 | govtrack = 412526 | opencong = 412526 | rollcall = 46138 | politifact = ron-desantis | fec = C00511568  | opensecrets = N00034746 | assets = | legistorm = | followthemoney =  | ontheissues = FL/Ron_DeSantis.htm | congress = ron-desantis/2116 | worldcat = | c-span = rondesantis | rose = | imdb =  | bloomberg = | nyt = | wsj = | washpo = 9f576f4a-4bbb-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cliff Stearns]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Florida|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Florida's 6th congressional district]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]]<br><small>D-[[Maryland]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority